An autotroph is an organism that produces organic compounds from carbon dioxide using either light or reactions of inorganic chemical compounds as a source of energy. An autotroph is known as a producer in a food chain. Plants and other organisms that carry out photosynthesis are phototrophs.

Autotrophs are a vital part of the food chains of all ecosystems. They take energy from the sun (or from other sources) and convert it into a form that is used to carry out various biological functions such as cell growth and respiration.